There are a number of issues with the code in the question; three different API&#39;s (Firebase RealTime Database, Firestore and Realm) which I think may be causing some of the confusion.

Let&#39;s cut to the chase with a straight Firestore answer. This code will read documents within a Firestore collection, create PhotoClass objects based on that data and store them in an array. Assume the structure is this

    photos //a collection
       photo_0 //a document
          byUserName: &quot;Henry&quot;
          byId: &quot;uid_0&quot;
       photo_1
          byUserName: &quot;George&quot;
          byId: &quot;uid_1&quot;

Here&#39;s a PhotoClass - I am defaulting the properties to empty strings instead of nils to reduce the need to handle nils. Since we are not using Realm, I also removed the Object definition and changed the vars to Swift vars instead of ObjC vars required by Realm (@objc dynamic)

    class PhotoClass {
        var photoId = &quot;&quot;
        var byId = &quot;&quot;
        var byUsername = &quot;&quot;
        //var date:String?
        //var url:String?
        //var postId:String?
        
        init(withDocumentSnapshot: DocumentSnapshot) {
            self.photoId = withDocumentSnapshot.documentID
            self.byUsername = withDocumentSnapshot.get(&quot;userName&quot;) as? String ?? &quot;No User Name&quot;
            self.byId = withDocumentSnapshot.get(&quot;byId&quot;) as? String ?? &quot;No uid&quot;
        }
    }

Note that I am defaulting values to a known string in case the read properties are nil. That way the app won&#39;t crash if a property is missing or nil. If you want to work with nil values, that&#39;s cool, but you have to protect your code by safely working with them throughout.

Then an array to store the photo&#39;s in

    var photosArray = [PhotoClass]()

Then the code to read on all of the documents within the photos node, create the PhotoClass objects and populate an array

    func readAllPhotos() {
        let photosCollection = self.db.collection(&quot;photos&quot;)
        photosCollection.getDocuments(completion: { snapshot, err in
            if let err = err {
                print(err.localizedDescription)
                return
            }
            
            for doc in snapshot!.documents {
                let photo = PhotoClass(withDocumentSnapshot: doc)
                self.photosArray.append(photo)
            }
        })
    }

Again, noting there is code in place to check for errors and protect the app in case the node is not found or some other error occurs.

