answers.body_markdown:
Standard library function `qsort`.

    void qsort(void *base, size_t nmemb, size_t size,
                  int (*compar)(const void *, const void *));

The array to be sorted is passed in `base`, its length in `nmemb`, the size of each element in `size` and the comparison function in `compar`.

Invocation looks something like this:

    char **strings = NULL;
    size_t nstrings = 0;
    // do something to load strings;

    //...

    // sort the strings
    qsort(strings, nstrings, sizeof(char *), string_comparer);


    int string_comparer(const void *a, const void *b) { return strcmp(*(const char *)a, *const char *b); }

This API feels a little old and clunky because of the lack of a baton to pass to the function, but with the `gcc` extension allowing inner functions to access variables in outer functions this is no longer a real problem.

Somebody&#39;s mirror of glibc&#39;s `qsort` is here: https://code.woboq.org/userspace/glibc/stdlib/qsort.c.html and a kernel version is here: https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/8a72f3820c4d14b27ad5336aed00063a7a7f1bef/lib/sort.c

