**NOTE:** OP just edited the question to add a requirement to use array instead, but I left my original answer at the bottom in case it would help anyone. 

----------

If the requirement is to use an array, then you would not need to assign variables at all. You could simply use the array, push into it and iterate as you need to. I would also assume that the assignment wants you to get comfortable with working with arrays.

This would work as a quick solution, but since this is your assignment it would be best for you to understand it and write your own solution:

    let array = []

    // function to return length of all characters in array
    const countFunc = array =&gt; {
        return array.join(&#39;&#39;).length
    }

    // Keep asking user for input until the count is at least 25
    while (countFunc(array) &lt; 25) {
        array.push(prompt(&quot;Enter string&quot;))
    }

The resulting array would look like:

    [&quot;some string&quot;, &quot;another string&quot;...]

----------

**Original answer:**

It would be better if you used an object instead of creating variables for each prompt, as you are unsure of how many variables you need, from a minimum of 1 to maximum of 25 (or more, if you allow submission of empty strings &quot;&quot;)

By using an object, I mean:

    let obj = {}, index = 0
    
    // Your function to count the total number of characters
    const countFunc = obj =&gt; {
        ...
    }
    
    // Keep asking user for input until the count is at least 25
    while (countFunc(obj) &lt; 25) {
         obj[index] = prompt(&quot;Enter string...&quot;)
         index++
    }

The result of your object will look like:

    {
        0: &quot;some string&quot;,
        1: &quot;another string&quot;
        ...
    }

Then you can access each value by its index when you need it. 

Note: You do not have use a numeric index as keys for your object, but in your case an incrementing index if easier instead of using random words, timestamp or random numbers.  

Your count function would look something like:

    const countFunc = obj =&gt; {
        let totalLength = 0
        // Loop through all keys in object,
        // add the length of each string
        Object.keys(obj).forEach(key =&gt; {
            totalLength += obj[key].length
        })
        return totalLength
    }

Alternatively you could use a reduce function to get the total length from the object keys as well.

